# btrfs — copy-on-write filesystem primer
#
# btrfs (B-tree filesystem, "butter fs" or "better fs" depending who you
# ask) is a copy-on-write filesystem with first-class support for
# snapshots, subvolumes, transparent compression, checksums, and
# multi-device pools. it's the only mainline-linux fs that bundles
# volume management AND filesystem in one layer — zfs's closest cousin
# in tree.
#
# DISTROS THAT USE BTRFS BY DEFAULT (root filesystem)
#
# - openSUSE Tumbleweed   — root on btrfs + snapper auto-snapshots
#                           on every zypper transaction. the canonical
#                           "btrfs done right" reference setup.
# - openSUSE Leap         — same as Tumbleweed.
# - SUSE Linux Enterprise — root on btrfs + snapper, /home often xfs.
# - Fedora Workstation    — root on btrfs since Fedora 33 (2020).
#                           no auto-snapshots out of the box.
# - Fedora Silverblue/Kinoite — btrfs + rpm-ostree on top.
# - Garuda Linux          — btrfs + snapper + grub-btrfs by default
#                           (the "arch + auto-snapshots" sell).
# - Synology DSM          — btrfs is the recommended fs on Plus/XS NAS
#                           units; powers snapshot replication.
# - Spiral Linux, Siduction, several other niche debian respins.
#
# distros where btrfs is OFFERED but not default: arch (manual partition
# step), ubuntu (server installer offers it, desktop defaults to ext4
# — canonical has historically kept distance from btrfs), debian
# (installer option, ext4 default), nixos (option, ext4 default).
#
# mental model worth knowing up front:
#
# - SUBVOLUME — an independently-mountable named tree inside the fs.
#   roughly "a directory you can snapshot and mount separately". the
#   top-level fs is itself subvolume id 5.
# - SNAPSHOT — a writable (or read-only) copy of a subvolume that
#   shares blocks via copy-on-write. taking one is O(1) and uses
#   ~zero space until something diverges.
# - PROFILE — how data and metadata are laid out across devices:
#   single / dup / raid0 / raid1 / raid10 / raid1c3 / raid1c4 / raid5
#   / raid6. raid5/6 are still considered unstable for metadata — use
#   raid1/raid10 for metadata even on a raid5 data pool.
# - CHECKSUMS — every data and metadata block is checksummed. silent
#   corruption is DETECTED on read; with a raid1+ profile it's
#   automatically REPAIRED from the good copy.
# - COMPRESSION — transparent, per-mount or per-file. zstd is the
#   modern default; older systems used lzo.
# - SCRUB — read-everything-and-verify operation. cron / systemd
#   timer this monthly on any production filesystem.
#
# command surface — almost everything is `btrfs <group> <verb>`:
#
#   btrfs subvolume       — create / delete / list / snapshot / set-default
#   btrfs filesystem      — show / df / usage / resize / defragment / sync
#   btrfs device          — add / remove / replace / scan / stats
#   btrfs balance         — rewrite blocks (rebalance, convert profiles)
#   btrfs scrub           — start / status / cancel / resume
#   btrfs send / receive  — incremental snapshot streaming
#   btrfs property        — get/set per-subvolume properties (ro, compression)
#   btrfs quota / qgroup  — quota groups (off by default; expensive)
#   btrfs check           — offline fsck. UNMOUNTED ONLY. read-only by default.
#   btrfs rescue          — recovery tools for broken fs


CREATING / MOUNTING
-------------------

# make a new btrfs filesystem on a single device
sudo mkfs.btrfs /dev/sdX

# multi-device fs in one call: raid1 for metadata + data
sudo mkfs.btrfs -d raid1 -m raid1 /dev/sda /dev/sdb

# label it (handy for fstab / boot)
sudo mkfs.btrfs -L mydata /dev/sdX

# mount with the sensible everyday options:
#   compress=zstd:3     — transparent zstd compression (level 1-15)
#   noatime             — don't update file atime on read
#   space_cache=v2      — modern free-space cache
sudo mount -o compress=zstd:3,noatime,space_cache=v2 /dev/sdX /mnt/data

# mount a specific subvolume by name
sudo mount -o subvol=@home /dev/sdX /home

# mount a specific subvolume by id (the only way that survives renames)
sudo mount -o subvolid=257 /dev/sdX /home


SUBVOLUMES
----------

# show every subvolume on a mounted fs
sudo btrfs subvolume list /mnt/data
sudo btrfs subvolume list -t /                 # tabular
sudo btrfs subvolume list -p -q -u /           # with parent / uuid info

# create a new subvolume (must be inside an existing btrfs)
sudo btrfs subvolume create /mnt/data/projects

# delete a subvolume (NOT `rm -rf` — that deletes contents only)
sudo btrfs subvolume delete /mnt/data/projects

# show the default subvolume (mounted when no subvol= option is given)
sudo btrfs subvolume get-default /mnt/data
sudo btrfs subvolume set-default 257 /mnt/data

# show details about one subvolume
sudo btrfs subvolume show /mnt/data/projects


SNAPSHOTS
---------

# snapshot a subvolume. instant, almost-zero space.
sudo btrfs subvolume snapshot /mnt/data/projects \
    /mnt/data/.snapshots/projects-2026-06-14

# READ-ONLY snapshot — the right kind for backups and send/receive
sudo btrfs subvolume snapshot -r /mnt/data/projects \
    /mnt/data/.snapshots/projects-2026-06-14

# read-only snapshots can be promoted to writable later
sudo btrfs property set /mnt/data/.snapshots/projects-2026-06-14 ro false

# delete a snapshot — exactly the same command as deleting a subvolume
sudo btrfs subvolume delete /mnt/data/.snapshots/projects-2026-06-14

# common pattern: rollback by swapping default subvolume to a snapshot
# (root fs rollback works this way on opensuse via snapper).
sudo btrfs subvolume set-default <snapshot-id> /


FREE SPACE — `df` LIES, USE btrfs filesystem usage
--------------------------------------------------

# `df -h` on a btrfs is misleading: it doesn't account for the
# allocation-vs-use distinction or for raid overhead. always cross-check:
sudo btrfs filesystem usage /
sudo btrfs filesystem df /                      # by block group type

# show device-level allocation
sudo btrfs filesystem show /
sudo btrfs filesystem show --mounted

# the "no space left on device" trap: btrfs can ENOSPC on metadata
# while data still looks free. fix is a balance (see below) or
# allocating one more chunk of metadata.


BALANCE — REBALANCE / RESHAPE / DEFRAG
--------------------------------------

# balance rewrites blocks across devices. used for: reclaiming
# half-empty chunks, changing raid profile, adding/removing a device.
# can take HOURS on a big fs. start with filters to bound the work.

# light balance — only reclaim chunks <50% full (cheap, fast)
sudo btrfs balance start -dusage=50 -musage=50 /

# convert from single to raid1 (after adding the 2nd device)
sudo btrfs balance start -dconvert=raid1 -mconvert=raid1 /mnt/data

# check progress
sudo btrfs balance status /
sudo btrfs balance pause /
sudo btrfs balance resume /
sudo btrfs balance cancel /

# defragment a file or directory (CoW means random writes fragment
# heavily — defrag helps especially for VM images and databases).
# WARNING: defrag breaks reflinks/snapshots — defragged extents are
# copied, so the snapshot stops sharing storage with the live file.
sudo btrfs filesystem defragment -r -czstd /var/lib/mysql


COMPRESSION
-----------

# enable for the whole mount via mount option
mount -o remount,compress=zstd:3 /mnt/data

# enable as a per-subvolume default (sticks across mounts)
sudo btrfs property set /mnt/data/projects compression zstd

# force-compress files already on disk
sudo btrfs filesystem defragment -r -czstd /mnt/data/projects

# disable compression for one path (e.g. databases that compress
# their own data, where double-compression wastes CPU)
sudo chattr +C /mnt/data/postgres                # no-CoW + no compression
sudo btrfs property set /mnt/data/postgres compression none


SCRUB — CHECKSUM VERIFICATION
-----------------------------

# read every block and verify its checksum. on a multi-device raid
# profile, silently REPAIRS damaged copies from the good mirror.
# do this MONTHLY on production data. timer-driven cron is fine.
sudo btrfs scrub start /
sudo btrfs scrub status /
sudo btrfs scrub cancel /
sudo btrfs scrub resume /

# error counters per device (uncorrectable read/write/flush errors —
# accumulate over time; any nonzero number deserves investigation).
sudo btrfs device stats /


DEVICES — ADD / REMOVE / REPLACE
--------------------------------

# add a new device to a live fs
sudo btrfs device add /dev/sdc /mnt/data
sudo btrfs balance start -dconvert=raid1 -mconvert=raid1 /mnt/data

# remove a device — btrfs first migrates its data off, then detaches
sudo btrfs device remove /dev/sdb /mnt/data

# replace a failing device IN PLACE (faster + safer than add+remove)
sudo btrfs replace start /dev/sdb /dev/sdd /mnt/data
sudo btrfs replace status /mnt/data

# scan all block devices for btrfs (needed if mounting by UUID
# pre-systemd-detect, or after a hotplug)
sudo btrfs device scan


SEND / RECEIVE — INCREMENTAL BACKUPS
------------------------------------

# `btrfs send` streams a read-only snapshot's differences over a pipe.
# `btrfs receive` reconstructs it on the other side. zero parsing of
# files involved — it's filesystem-level. fast, exact, and
# incrementals are O(changes), not O(filesystem-size).

# initial full send to another btrfs fs (mounted at /backup/)
sudo btrfs subvolume snapshot -r /home /home/.snap/2026-06-14
sudo btrfs send /home/.snap/2026-06-14 | sudo btrfs receive /backup/

# incremental against the previous snapshot (-p = parent)
sudo btrfs subvolume snapshot -r /home /home/.snap/2026-06-15
sudo btrfs send -p /home/.snap/2026-06-14 /home/.snap/2026-06-15 \
    | sudo btrfs receive /backup/

# over ssh
sudo btrfs send -p /home/.snap/2026-06-14 /home/.snap/2026-06-15 \
    | ssh backup-host sudo btrfs receive /backup/


SNAPPER (the openSUSE / SUSE auto-snapshot tool)
------------------------------------------------

# on opensuse this is preinstalled and wired into zypper, taking pre-
# and post-snapshots around every transaction. on other distros you
# install it:
sudo apt install snapper                          # debian / ubuntu
sudo dnf install snapper                          # fedora
sudo pacman -S snapper                            # arch / manjaro
sudo zypper install snapper                       # opensuse (usually preinstalled)

# create a config for a subvolume (creates /etc/snapper/configs/<name>)
sudo snapper -c root create-config /

# list snapshots
sudo snapper -c root list

# take a manual snapshot
sudo snapper -c root create --description "before-mariadb-upgrade"

# diff between two snapshots
sudo snapper -c root status 42..43
sudo snapper -c root diff 42..43

# rollback to a snapshot (subvolume swap + reboot)
sudo snapper -c root rollback 42

# on opensuse, grub2-snapper-plugin adds "Bootable snapshots" submenu
# to grub so you can boot directly into a pre-update snapshot.


COMMON GOTCHAS
--------------

# 1. databases and VM images fragment heavily under CoW. mark them
#    nodatacow with `chattr +C` BEFORE writing data, on an empty
#    directory. chattr +C on an existing file does nothing for
#    already-written extents.
sudo mkdir /var/lib/mysql
sudo chattr +C /var/lib/mysql
# now restore / initdb

# 2. raid5 and raid6 are NOT production-ready for metadata. always
#    use `-m raid1` or `-m raid1c3` for metadata even on raid5 data.

# 3. `btrfs check --repair` is a LAST RESORT. it can make things
#    worse. always try `btrfs scrub` and `btrfs rescue zero-log`
#    first, and clone the device with ddrescue before any --repair.

# 4. `df` reports allocation, not files. an "almost full" btrfs may
#    have lots of half-empty chunks; a balance with `-dusage=50` is
#    often the fix. conversely an "empty looking" btrfs may already
#    be metadata-full and refuse writes.

# 5. quota groups (qgroup) are powerful but expensive — they slow
#    balance and delete significantly. keep them off unless you
#    need them.

# 6. don't snapshot $HOME if it contains a live VM image or a
#    busy db unless those paths are marked nodatacow — the
#    snapshot will pin growing-but-no-longer-shared blocks and
#    blow up your disk usage.

# 7. trim / discard on SSDs: use `fstrim` periodically (or the
#    fstrim.timer) rather than mount option `discard` — async
#    trim has historically had btrfs-specific quirks.


RECOVERY
--------

# UNMOUNTED check (btrfs check is offline-only). default is read-only:
sudo btrfs check /dev/sdX                         # safe; analyses only
sudo btrfs check --readonly /dev/sdX              # explicit

# rescue tools (try these before any --repair)
sudo btrfs rescue zero-log /dev/sdX               # clears stale log
sudo btrfs rescue super-recover /dev/sdX          # repairs superblock from backups
sudo btrfs rescue chunk-recover /dev/sdX          # rebuild chunk tree

# mount a damaged fs read-only with backup superblock + recovery
sudo mount -o ro,rescue=all /dev/sdX /mnt/rescue

# list backup superblocks
sudo btrfs inspect-internal dump-super -fa /dev/sdX


